reference "sec:FPA-FTIR-microscopy"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analyses of the stitched FPA-FTIR image of the normal to cancer graduated
 bronchiole biopsy show that different lung tissue types can be distinguished
 when analysing 64x64 co-added and averaged pixels.
 Distinctions can be made using the peak height of the second derivative
 trough at 1556 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

, but more effectively the two cell types can be separated into two groups
 by hierarchical clustering of the 1575-1450 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 region.
 However disease state cannot be distinguished with only 64x64 binned pixels.
 If larger areas of each disease state are manually selected and their averages
 compared, differences between normal, mild dysplasia, severe dysplasia
 and cancer can be seen in regions 1300-1250 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 1150-1070 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Where 1070 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the spectral cutoff due to noise exceeding the signal with the parameters
 used in this particular experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate-Resume
