reference "sec:ATR-FTIR"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eighty fresh lung biopsies were recently collected and measured using ATR-FTIR
 spectroscopy.
 After separating the four histologically classified groups (normal, LGD,
 HGD and cancer) into their sidedness using information from FPA-FTIR microscopy
, disease stage differences can be noted in both the surface of the biopsy,
 the epithelium, and the underlying side of the biopsy, the lamina propria.
 In the epithelium tissue the most prominent differences occurred in the
 lipid region 1738 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

, between 1300-1250 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and between 1100-950 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the lamina propria, cancerous tissue has a larger lipid band at 1738
 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 than the other classes of lung biopsies, and the 1190-1140 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 shows a possible transition from healthy to cancerous biopsies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These initial results are encouraging with only 80 biopsies.
 Additional data should further resolve these spectral differences.
\end_layout

