\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to detect the subtle differences between NDBE and HGD IR signatures,
 the noise has to be significantly lower than the discriminatory signal(s).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The single element ATR-FTIR difference spectra of the of 36 averaged NDBE
 surface biopsies and 31 averaged HGD surface biopsies (approximately 5
 mm
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

 in size), together with their original spectrum, is shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:ATR-FTIR-dys-changes"

\end_inset

.
 It is most likely that the largest difference (1635 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:ATR-FTIR-dys-changes"

\end_inset

b.) is due to differences in water contributions, and not related to differences
 in the disease state of the tissue.
 Therefore, the next most significant difference between the two tissue
 types is at 1090-1036 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This typically has an absorbance difference of 0.0015 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:ATR-FTIR-dys-changes"

\end_inset

 b) in relation to the amide II signal intensity of 0.02 in their normalised
 absolute spectra (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:ATR-FTIR-dys-changes"

\end_inset

 a).
 Therefore, the difference signal: amide II ratio is 0.075.
 More generally, un-normalised biopsy amide II signal intensities average
 around 0.07 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:a)-ATR-noise"

\end_inset

 a), so that the expected difference between NDBE and HGD at 1090-1036 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 would be 0.005.
 The underlying thermal noise in this region, based on 500 co-added interferogra
ms of both the sample and the background at 4 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 resolution using a SensIR 3-reflection silicon prism is approx.
 3.6 x 10
\begin_inset Formula $^{-5}$
\end_inset

 when calculated from a moving average of the peak heights with a 54 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 window (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:a)-ATR-noise"

\end_inset

 b).
 A window of this size was chosen as this is the width from 1090-1036 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the signal:noise ratio at 1036 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 was approx.
 150.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This does not take into account other factors that might distort the baseline
 and decrease this ratio.
 However, it should also be noted that the single element system is averaging
 the spectra of many individual cells, and there will inevitably be mixtures
 of cell types in such samples.
 Hence, the distinguishing factor may appear as a greater percentage of
 the amide II band in single cell IR spectra.
\end_layout

