\begin_layout Subsection
Calculation of FPA-FTIR Microscopy of Dysplastic Lung Biopsy signal:noise
 ratios
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
FPA-FTIR Microscopy signal:noise ratio calculations
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine the signal: noise ratio requirement of FPA-FTIR microscopy
 to discriminate dysplastic from normal regions, a deparaffinised, 8 µm
 dysplastic lung biopsy section was used.
 A 96x96 element Focal Plane Array (FPA) detector was used for the measurements,
 this gave a projected pixel size of 2.7 µm
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Spectra of each element were calculated from 128 co-added interferograms
 at a 4 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 resolution.
 The transmission image was obtained using a lens on top of the CaF
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 window to create a pseudo hemisphere in order to focus the IR light, and
 reduce light scattering.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The amide II signals varied between 0.05 and 0.3.
 Using the mean amide II signal of 0.1, the expected difference signal between
 dysplastic and normal tissue at 1090-1036 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is therefore estimated at 0.0075 absorbance units when based on the calculations
 in the above section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Single-Element-ATR-FTIR"

\end_inset

 - 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sub:Single-Element-ATR-FTIR"

\end_inset

.
 The underlying thermal noise across the FPA detector varied significantly,
 this is most likely due to varying intensity of the power spectrum.
 However this would need to be confirmed by analysis of the power spectrum.
 The noise level was improved by the co-addition and averaging blocks of
 64 adjacent pixels, in 8x8 matrices.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:FTIR-image-S2N-ratio"

\end_inset

 shows the standard deviation, mean and range of the amide II heights and
 the signal:noise ratios of thermal noise from the 1090-1036 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 region of blank regions of the image that have also been co-adding and
 averaged spectra from blocks of 64 pixels.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:a)-FTIRimage-typical"

\end_inset

b shows examples of baseline spectra from such binned blocks of pixels that
 were selected from regions of the image where no sample was present.
 The signal:noise ratio of 1.0 (
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

0.5 s.d.) determined for binned 8x8 pixel blocks, is at the limit for detection
 of the dysplasia-related discriminatory band difference at 1090-1036 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 It should be noted that this signal: noise ratio calculation is an estimate
 as it assumes that the signal between ATR-FTIR and transmission are directly
 comparable.
 In ATR-FTIR spectroscopy a signal at ratio of 1000cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

:1600 cm
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 would be higher than the same ratio in transmission mode because of the
 ramping effect in ATR due to depth of penetration verses frequency.
\end_layout

